{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489106"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/593"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.04,0.73,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31198"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/593"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17066"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31198"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents with acute onset of painful right eye movements in all directions. Her left eye is normal. This is her first episode. There is no history of trauma. She describes \u0027blurry\u0027 vision with \u0027flickering\u0027 in her peripheral visual field. She denies headache, neck pain, or speech disturbance. She has had weakness in both her legs, which was noticed two days ago after a hot shower. Her bladder and bowel continence are intact. A fundoscopic examination of the right eye demonstrates optic disc swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar puncture","Retinal scan","Optic ultrasound","MRI with gadolinium contrast","Electromyography"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is suggestive of a first presentation of demyelinating disorder, specifically multiple sclerosis, given her symptoms of optic neuritis as well as worsening of symptoms following a hot shower, termed Uhthoff phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultiple sclerosis is an immune-mediated inflammatory demyelinating disease of the central nervous system. Suggestive features include female predominance, relapses and remissions, onset between ages 15 yo 50, optic neuritis, internuclear ophthalmoplegia, fatigue and heat sensitivity (Uhthoff phenomenon).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of multiple sclerosis should be made using the McDonald crtiteria with evidence of a central nervous system lesion disseminated in time and space, either clinically or radiographically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI with gadolinium\u003C/strong\u003E is the test of choice as it is able to demonstrate lesions (plaques) in the cerebral hemispheres or spine. MRI is able to detect more lesions than CT, in particular in regions such as brainstem, cerebellum and spinal cord. A lumbar puncture, similarly, may help to differentiate from other neurologic causes but is in itself not a requirement for diagnosis of MS. Evaluation for oligoclonal IGG bands and elevated immunoglobulin (predominantly IgG) production is a common finding in MS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["MRI is the first line investigation in a patient with a suspected demyelinating disorder."],"references":["Garg N, Smith TW. An update on immunopathogenesis, diagnosis, and treatment of multiple sclerosis. Brain Behav. 2015;5(9):e00362."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17066"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17066"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-31T14:00:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-31T14:00:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"593"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31198"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/279"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Multiple sclerosis","synonyms":["MS"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:13:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta